Boil a #pot{} of water with @salt{1/2%tsp} for your @new potatoes{2}. Chop the new
potatoes into quarters.

Chop off the root and the green leafy part of the @leeks{4}. Slice the leeks in
half lengthways and then very, very thinly slice widthways.

Heat @olive oil{2%tbsp} in a #frying pan{} on medium heat and add the leeks. Cook
them gently for around ~{10%minutes} until soft and sweet. Remove from the heat.

Lay each @British chicken breasts{4} on a #chopping board{} and slice into it from
the side. Open it up like a book. You've now butterflied your chicken!

> Tip: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Turn your grill to high heat. Rub a little bit of @olive oil{} onto each chicken
breast. Season with a little pinch of @salt{} and @ground black pepper{} and lay
on a #baking tray{}. Place under your #grill{} on the highest shelf for
~{5-6%minutes} on one side, then take the tray out from under your grill, turn
the chicken breasts over and pop back under the grill to cook for another
~{5-6%minutes}.

Whilst your chicken is grilling, add your potatoes to the pot of boiling water,
for ~{10%minutes}. Tip: The potatoes are cooked when you can easily stick a
knife through them. Once they are cooked, drain them.

Crumble the @feta cheese{2} into the cooled leek mixture. Taste the mixture and
add a bit of salt and pepper if it needs it.

> Tip: Feta is pretty salty already, so make sure you taste as you go to get the
> seasoning just right.

Spread your leek mixture over the top of your grilled chicken and put back under
the grill. Cook for another ~{1-2%minutes} until the top is nice and golden.

Once drained, toss your potatoes in a little @?butter{} if you have some (or some
@olive oil{}). Sprinkle over a little @salt{} and @ground black pepper{}. Finely
shred the @mint{4} leaves and sprinkle them over your potatoes. Serve with your
chicken on the side and savour!